p Traditional advertising is!{' '}
  span.bold less
  |!{' '}effective than ever before. It interrupts. It can’t get through ad blockers. We’ve learned to ignore it.
p Having fans sell your product is!{' '}
  span.bold more
  |!{' '}effective than ever before.
p Tesla grasp this. They have zero advertising budget. The focus is on!{' '}
  span.bold turning customers into fans
  | . And it's fair to say they've succeeded:
img(src="https://harrydry.s3.amazonaws.com/gdmarketing/tesla1.png" alt="Graph of Tesla's Subreddit size and Twitter following").img__90
h2 Authenticity
p If I had one just one word to summarise Tesla's success it would be!{' '}
  span.bold authenticity
  | . They are unashamedly!{' '}
  span.italic themselves
  | .
p The car makes!{' '}
  a(href="https://youtu.be/rfB4v-VF7zg?t=139" target="_blank") “fart noises”
  | . Their CEO makes!{' '}
  a(href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1199723451008704513" target="_blank") memes
  | . And, simultaneously, they have the best engineers in the world working on a solution to the fossil fuel crisis.
p The result is both
  |!{' '}one of the most!{' '}
  span.bold carefree
  |!{' '}and one of the most!{' '}
  span.bold ambitious
  |!{' '}brands on the planet. It's!{' '}
  a(href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vxRqPmvGlUY" target="_blank") Weasley's Wizard Wheezes
  |!{' '}meets Tony Stark. And the juxtaposition is captivating.
h2 Controversy
p If authenticity is how to!{' '}
  span.bold connect
  |!{' '}with an audience, controversy is how to!{' '}
  span.bold multiply
  |!{' '}an audience. And Musk is the master of this:
p He smokes weed with Joe Rogan, sells flamethrowers, blasts a Tesla into orbit, and then when it’s time to launch a real product!{' '}
  span.bold he’s got our attention
  | .
p Imagine any other automobile company attracting the world's media to a launch event, smashing two windows, and selling 250k+ units upfront:
img(src="https://harrydry.s3.amazonaws.com/gdmarketing/tesla2.jpg" alt="Tesla's YouTube fans").img__95
p.asterix * * *
p Competitors spend hundreds of thousands of dollars for a 30 second commercial to play during a basketball game.
p Tesla sit back and watch their fans make these videos for them. An army of YouTubers explaining “Why I bought the new Cybertruck” in a far more sincere way than any commercial could:
img(src="https://harrydry.s3.amazonaws.com/gdmarketing/tesla3.jpg" alt="Laura Elizabeth Twitter").img__95
p And the numbers are frightening:
p.inwardSpeech 6.9M views * 1 / 5000 conversion = 1,380 Cybertrucks
p That's!{' '}
  span.bold $75M
  |!{' '}revenue. From just 1 video.
h2.under What can we learn from Tesla?
p Well, if the best salespeople are your customers perhaps marketing should be a little less about!{' '}
  span.bold attracting eyeballs
  |!{' '}and a little more about!{' '}
  span.bold building relationships
  | .
p Instead of asking “How many views?” ask yourself “How many fans?”
p I experienced this on a micro level last week. One organic tweet from!{' '}
  a(href="https://twitter.com/laurium" target="_blank") Laura
  |!{' '}resulted in!{' '}
  span.bold 5x
  |!{' '}as many newsletter sign ups as!{' '}
  span.bold $30
  |!{' '}worth of Facebook ads:
